🏠 Home — Canonical Specification

Version: v1.0
Status: Locked
Applies to: Keystone App
Last Updated: 2026-01-21

0. Purpose (Non-Negotiable)

Home exists for two things only:

Unload — get things out of the user’s mind immediately

Orient — help the user understand whether anything in their life or finances needs attention, in human language

If Home does anything else, it is incorrect.

1. Home’s Core Question

When a user opens Home, Keystone must answer this within ~5 seconds:

“Am I okay right now — and can I put this down?”

Every design, interaction, and line of copy must serve this feeling.

Home is not a dashboard.
Home is not a workspace.
Home is not a list.

Home is a psychological stabiliser.

2. Home Structure (What Exists)

Home contains exactly two primary elements:

[ Unload Input (with AI inference) ]
[ Orientation (AI conclusions) ]


Nothing else is permitted.

No sections

No cards

No titles

No grids

No lists

No history

Whitespace is intentional and functional.

3. Unload (Primary Interaction)
3.1 What the User Sees

A single, prominent input area

Calm, neutral styling

No mode selection

No instructional UI

Placeholder (locked):

What’s on your mind?

No helper text unless required for accessibility.

3.2 What the User Does

The user types anything, including but not limited to:

A thought

A worry

A question

A half-formed decision

Emotional text

Practical text

Sentence fragments

The user is not deciding what this is.

3.3 What Happens on Submit (Critical)

When the user submits input:

The input clears

A brief, soft confirmation appears, then fades:

“Saved.”

or “Held.”

There is:

No redirect

No forced response

No follow-up unless implicitly invited

This moment is the release moment.

4. AI Behaviour Inside Unload (Key Feature)

AI is always present inside Unload.

The user never chooses a mode.

4.1 AI Inference

AI silently infers intent, such as:

Pure off-loading

Uncertainty

Question

Decision-shaped input

Emotional load

This inference exists to reduce cognitive effort for the user.

4.2 AI Responses (Conditional)

Based on inference, AI may:

Do nothing (most common and valid)

Offer a gentle reflection (1–2 sentences)

Ask one clarifying question

Suggest holding this as a draft decision

Automatically create a draft decision in the background without interrupting

Rules:

No analysis unless invited

No productivity language

No obligation to continue

Silence is always acceptable

Unload is intelligent off-loading, not dumb capture.

5. Orientation (AI Conclusions About Life & Money)

Orientation is separate from the input and never competes with it.

5.1 What Orientation Is

Orientation is AI-generated conclusions, synthesised from:

Accounts

Bills

Income

Decisions

Reviews

Thresholds

Patterns

Orientation answers one question only:

“Is there anything I should be aware of right now?”

5.2 What the User Sees

One or a small number of human-written sentences

Calm, non-urgent language

No raw data

No numbers

No lists

No explanations

Examples (directional, not final copy):

“Everything looks steady right now.”

“One upcoming bill may need a look.”

“You’re safe to spend within your usual range.”

“There’s a decision here that could reduce stress later.”

Orientation appears only when there is something meaningful to say.

Silence is valid and intentional.

5.3 Interaction Rules

Orientation items may be clickable

Clicking always navigates the user away from Home

No inline expansion

No modals

No explanation unless the user chooses to go deeper

Home remains a place of rest.

6. Relationship Between Unload and Orientation

Unload and Orientation are distinct, but connected over time.

Unload = what’s in the user’s mind

Orientation = what’s happening in the user’s life

They do not react to each other in real time.

However:

What the user unloads may influence future orientation

Over time, AI learns what matters to the user

This learning must remain invisible and non-intrusive

Trust is built quietly.

7. What Home Explicitly Does NOT Do

Home does not:

Show balances

Show bills

Show tasks

Show decision lists

Show captured items

Show history

Ask questions by default

Require action

Explain itself

Anything that increases cognitive load does not belong on Home.

8. Emotional Success Criteria (Primary Test)

Home is correct if:

A tired parent opens the app

Types one sentence

Sees a calm orientation (or silence)

Closes the app

Feels lighter

If this does not happen, remove something.

Never add.

9. Engineering Guardrails

One page

One primary input

Orientation rendered only when AI has something meaningful to say

Never stack multiple orientation messages

No urgency language

No visual noise

If an engineer asks, “Can we also show…”
The answer is No.

10. Internal Definition (Single Line)

Home is where users unload what’s on their mind, and where AI quietly tells them whether anything in their life or finances needs attention — in human language.

End of document.